SIMPLE: form
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -form
<hw>-form</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>Form</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A suffix used to denote <sig>in the form
<it>or</it> shape of</sig>, <sig>resembling</sig>, etc.; <as>as,
vali<ex>form</ex>; ovi<ex>form</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Form</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Form
<hw>Form</hw> <pr>(f⟦omac⟧rm; <xex>in senses</xex> 8 & 9,
<xex>often</xex> f⟦omac⟧rm <xex>in England</xex>)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. & F. <ets>forme</ets>, fr. L. <ets>forma</ets>; cf. Skr.
<ets>dhariman</ets>. Cf. <er>Firm</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
shape and structure of anything, as distinguished from the material of
which it is composed; particular disposition or arrangement of matter,
giving it individuality or distinctive character; configuration; figure;
external appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>form</qex> of his visage was changed.</q> <rj><qau>Dan.
iii. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And woven close close, both matter, <qex>form</qex>, and
style.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Constitution; mode of construction, organization,
etc.; system; <as>as, a republican <ex>form</ex> of
government</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Established method of expression or practice; fixed
way of proceeding; conventional or stated scheme; formula; <as>as, a
<ex>form</ex> of prayer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those whom <qex>form</qex> of laws⟦br⟧
Condemned to die.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Show without substance; empty, outside appearance;
vain, trivial, or conventional ceremony; conventionality; formality;
<as>as, a matter of mere <ex>form</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though well we may not pass upon his life⟦br⟧
Without the <qex>form</qex> of justice.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Orderly arrangement; shapeliness; also, comeliness;
elegance; beauty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earth was without <qex>form</qex> and void.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
i. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath no <qex>form</qex> nor comeliness.</q> <rj><qau>Is. liii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A shape; an image; a phantom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>That by which shape is given or determined; mold;
pattern; model.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A long seat; a bench; hence, a rank of students in a
school; a class; also, a class or rank in society.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Ladies
of a high <xex>form</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp. Burnet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>The seat or bed of a hare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As in a <qex>form</qex> sitteth a weary hare.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>The type or other matter from
which an impression is to be taken, arranged and secured in a
chase.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>The boundary line of a
material object. In <fld>(painting)</fld>, more generally, the human
body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>The particular shape or
structure of a word or part of speech; <as>as, participial
<ex>forms</ex>; verbal <ex>forms</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>The combination of planes
included under a general crystallographic symbol. It is not necessarily
a closed solid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>That assemblage or disposition
of qualities which makes a conception, or that internal constitution
which makes an existing thing to be what it is; -- called
<xex>essential</xex> or <xex>substantial form</xex>, and
contradistinguished from <xex>matter</xex>; hence, active or formative
nature; law of being or activity; subjectively viewed, an idea;
objectively, a law.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <def>Mode of acting or manifestation to the senses, or
the intellect; <as>as, water assumes the <ex>form</ex> of ice or
snow</as>. In modern usage, the elements of a conception furnished by
the mind's own activity, as contrasted with its object or condition,
which is called the <xex>matter</xex>; subjectively, a mode of
apprehension or belief conceived as dependent on the constitution of the
mind; objectively, universal and necessary accompaniments or elements of
every object known or thought of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The peculiar characteristics of
an organism as a type of others; also, the structure of the parts of an
animal or plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 587 --></p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Good form</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Bad
form</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the general appearance, condition or action,
originally of horses, afterwards of persons; as, the members of a boat
crew are said to be in <ex>good form</ex> when they pull together
uniformly. The phrases are further used colloquially in description of
conduct or manners in society; as, it is not <ex>good form</ex> to smoke
in the presence of a lady.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Form</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Form
<hw>Form</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocir⟧rm)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Formed</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ocir⟧rmd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Forming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>former</ets>, L. <ets>formare</ets>, fr. <ets>forma</ets>. See
<er>Form</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To give form or
shape to; to frame; to construct; to make; to fashion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God <qex>formed</qex> man of the dust of the ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. ii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The thought that labors in my <qex>forming</qex> brain.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give a particular shape to; to shape, mold, or
fashion into a certain state or condition; to arrange; to adjust; also,
to model by instruction and discipline; to mold by influence, etc.; to
train.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is education <qex>forms</qex> the common mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus <qex>formed</qex> for speed, he challenges the wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To go to make up; to act as constituent of; to be
the essential or constitutive elements of; to answer for; to make the
shape of; -- said of that out of which anything is formed or
constituted, in whole or in part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The diplomatic politicians . . . who <qex>formed</qex> by far the
majority.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To provide with a form, as a hare. See
<er>Form</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 9.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The melancholy hare is <qex>formed</qex> in brakes and briers.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>To derive by grammatical rules,
as by adding the proper suffixes and affixes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>To treat (plates) so as to bring
them to fit condition for introduction into a storage battery, causing
one plate to be composed more or less of spongy lead, and the other of
lead peroxide. This was formerly done by repeated slow alternations of
the charging current, but now the plates or grids are coated or filled,
one with a paste of red lead and the other with litharge, introduced
into the cell, and <ex>formed</ex> by a direct charging
current.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Form</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Form
<hw>Form</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take a form,
definite shape, or arrangement; <as>as, the infantry should
<ex>form</ex> in column</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To run to a form, as a hare.</def> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To form on</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to form a
lengthened line with reference to (any given object) as a
basis.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Formal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Form
<hw>For`m⟦eacute⟧"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Her.)</fld>
<def>Same as <er>Pat⟦eacute⟧</er> or <er>Patt⟦eacute⟧</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forme</ent>⟦br⟧
